class ExamRoom {
    int[] seats;
    int n;

    public ExamRoom(int n) {
        this.n = n;
        seats = new int[n];
        Arrays.fill(seats, -1);
    }

    public int seat() {
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (seats[i] == -1) {
                seats[i] = i;
                return i;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }

    public void leave(int p) {
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (seats[p] == -1) {
                seats[p] = -1;
                return;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Solution:

Java solution for the ExamRoom class:

1. Initialize an array of size n to store the current seat numbers.
2. In the `seat()` method, iterate through the array and assign the current seat number to the index of the array where the seat number is -1. If a seat number is found, return it.
3. In the `leave()` method, iterate through the array and assign -1 to the index of the array where the seat number is found. If a seat number is found, return.

Efficiency:

Efficiency: HIGH
Time complexity: O(n)
Space complexity: O(1)
Energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The solution iterates through the array once to find the seat number and once more to assign -1 to the seat number index. The solution has a constant space complexity (O(1)) as it only uses a single integer array to store the seat numbers.

